<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="PN2-intro">
tiṇai – pāṭāṇṭiṇai; tuṟai ceviyaṟivuṟūu; vāḻttiyalumaṅama. cēramāṉ peruñcōṟṟu utiyaṉcēralātaṉai murañciyūr muṭinākarāyar pāṭiyatu.
‍      </p>
      <p xml:lang="en">  
      </p>
    </div>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="PN2">
<l>maṇṭiṇinta nilaṉum</l>
<l>nilaṉēntiya vicumpum</l>
<l>vicumputaivaru vaḷiyum</l>
<l>vaḷittalaiiya tīyun</l>
<l>tīmuraṇiya nīrumeṉṟāṅ</l>
<l>kaimperum pūtat tiyaṟkai pōlap</l>
<l>pōṟṟārp poṟuttaluñ cūḻcciya takalamum</l>
<l>valiyun teṟalu maḷiyu muṭaiyōy</l>
<l>niṉkaṭaṟ piṟanta ñāyiṟu peyarttuniṉ</l>
<l>veṇṭalaip puṇarik kuṭakaṭaṟ kuḷikkum</l>
<l>yāṇar vaippi ṉaṉṉāṭṭup poruna</l>
<l>vāṉa varampaṉai nīyō peruma</l>
<l>alaṅkuḷaip puravi yaivaroṭu ciṉaii</l>
<l>nilantalaik koṇṭa polanpūn tumpai</l>
<l>yīraim patiṉmarum porutukaḷat toḻiyap</l>
<l>peruñcōṟṟu mikupatam varaiyātu koṭuttōy</l>
<l>pāalpuḷippiṉum pakaliruḷiṉu</l>
<l>nāalvēta neṟitiriyiṉun</l>
<l>tiriyāc cuṟṟamoṭu muḻutucēṇ viḷaṅki</l>
<l>naṭukkiṉṟi niliyarō vattai yaṭukkattuc</l>
<l>ciṟutalai navvip peruṅkaṇ māppiṇai</l>
<l>yanti yantaṇa raruṅkaṭa ṉiṟukku</l>
<l>muttī viḷakkiṟ ṟuñcum</l>
<l>poṟkōṭ ṭimayamum potiyamum pōṉṟē</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>The ground that has solidified into earth, (1)</l>
<l>the sky held up by the ground, (2)</l>
<l>the wind that strokes the sky, (3)</l>
<l>the fire that is fanned by the wind, (4)</l>
<l>and the water that is opposed to fire, like [those], (5)</l>
<l>similar in nature to the five great elements (6)</l>
<l>you who possess [their] bearing with those who do not praise [you],</l>
<l>width of deliberation, strength, punishing, and care, (7f.)</l>
<l>o fighter of good lands with fertile regions, (11)</l>
<l>where the sun that is born in your sea again (9)</l>
<l>dips into your western ocean with white-headed waves, (10)</l>
<l>do you possess [but] the sky as a boundary, great man? (12)</l>
<l>You who have given without limit huge quantities of great rice (16)</l>
<l>when the twice Fifty stayed behind on the [battle] field after fighting, (15)</l>
<l>[wearing] Tumpai with golden flowers, who took the ground, (14)</l>
<l>raging along the with Five, [their] horses with swaying manes, (13)</l>
<l>even if milk were to turn sour, even if day were to turn dark, (17)</l>
<l>even if [people] were to swerve from the path of the fours Vedas, (18)</l>
<l>shining into the whole distance with a retinue that does not swerve, (19)</l>
<l>without shaking may you stand [fast], (20a-c)</l>
<l>similar to [mount] Potiyam and Imayam with golden peaks, (24)</l>
<l>where the big-eyed doe with [its] little-headed fawn (21)</l>
<l>sleeps in the light of the three fires (23)</l>
<l>when brahmins abide by [their] difficult duty in the twilight (22)</l>
	<l>on the mountain side. (20d)</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
